x4freetext: Run Cycle  FP Thickness Nominal Lab. Angles
samples of 35Cl as silver chloride and sodium chloride
were thermally evaporated onto 1.5 microm thick gold
backings at the University of Notre Dame.
The measurements were performed over the
2022 and 2023 run cycles of the LANSCE accelerator,
once again utilizing the 15R and 90L flight paths at
WNR. These two flight paths represent two different
angles and distances from the spallation neutron
source and therefore two different neutron flux
profiles. The 15R measurement (at a distance of 15.2
m) was optimized for higher incident neutron energies,
while at 90L, at a distance of 8.2 m, neutrons could
be resolved down to approximately 100 keV; however,
due to the rapidly decreasing 35Cl(n,p) cross
section and strong contributions from the LANSCE
proton dark current, we were limited to measure the
cross sections down to just below 300 keV in this work.
